{"/service/ndnp/in/batch_in_janeway_ver01/data/sn87055779/00383349898/1930121901/0269.xml":{"full_text":"-_\nAlways First\nSOUTH BEND NEWS-TIMES\nT\nAlways Fair\nDAT AND NIGHT flIL.LT LRASED\nWIRE. TELEGRAPHIC SERVICE\nSOUTH BEND, INDIANA. FRIDAY, DECEMBER 19, 1930\nPART TWO\nPOUCE DRAG RIVER FOR BODY OF MISSING LDMBER COMPANY OFFICIAL\n_\nLeslie\u2019s Proposed Sales Tax Heartily Scored at Meeting Held in Chamber of Commerce\nLATZ IN ADDRESS\nCLAIMS MEASURE\nHURTS POOR MAN\nPlan Would Retard Sales\nand Hurt Merchant,\nSpeaker Says.\nThe recommendation of Governor\nLeslie's tax commission for the\nenactment of a one per cent tax on\nthe sale of all merchandise in the\nstate of Indiana came under heavy\nfire at meeting of merchants and\nother members of the Chamber of\nCommerce Thursday.\nE. Irving Latz, Fort Wayne mer\nchant. addressed the gathering, at\ntacking the proposed tax as funda\nmentally unsound.\nState Senator Chester A. Perkins\nand State Representatives-elect John\nB. Kuespert, Charles J. Allardt and\nFrancis B. Salata were present at\nthe meeting and listened to the argu\nments.\nMight Reduce Purchasing,\n\u201cA direct charge on purchases of\nmerchandise, such as will be pro\nposed at the next meeting of the\nlegislature, would be bound to reduce\nthe purchasing power of the con\nsumer,\u201d Mr. Latz said.\nIt would definitely retard sales and\nwould do more to hamper the return\nof prosperity than anything I know\ncf.\n\"A sales tax would lower living\nstandards. It is definitely a poor man\u2019s\ntax. It is not comparable to the\ngasoline tax for which we get direct\nresults in road improvement.\n\u201cSuch a sales tax in Indiana would\ngive mail order houses a great ad\nvantage and would particularly hit\nthe small merchant. The cost of col\nlection would be tremendous.\u201d\nHapp Participated.\nWilliam Happ, real estate man,\nparticipated in the discussion main\ntaining that under present laws real\nestate bears an unfair portion of the\ntax burden while many owners of in\ntangibles escape fair assessments.\nMr. Latz said that merchants\nthroughout Indiaftia are voicing ob\njections to the sales tax.\nProposals for a state income tax\nwere also discussed and the sentiment\nappeared to be that as btween the\nUo, an income tax would be prefer\nable to a sales tax.\nThe Chamber of Commerce will\nprobably discuss the subject further.\nProposed changes in the Indiana\ntaxing system will be one of the\nprincipal subjects occupying atten\ntion of the state legislature at its\nsession which opens in a few weeks.\nSEEK TEMPORARY\nPOSTAL BUILDING\nTreasury Man Inspects\nLocations Available\nin Town.\nInspection of proposed local build\nings offered as temporary quarters for\nSouth Bend postal activities while the\npresent postoffice is being demolished\nto give way to a new $1,000,000 struc\nture was conducted by A. A. Packard,\nChicago, district representative of the\ntreasury department, in company\n\u2022with Joseph N. Toole, local postal\ninspector, Thursday.\nIt will probably be six months at\nleast before the postofflce must move\nfrom its present quarters, according\nto Postmaster John N. Hunter, who\nalso conferred with Mr. Packard.\nMany Locations Offered\nA number of locations have been\noffered to the postofflce department.\nIn addition to persons with vacant\nbuildings to lease, one offer was to\nerect a temporary building for post\noffice purposes.\nArchitects\u2019 pians for the new post\nefflee will be completed by Austin\nand Shambleau by March 1, and ad\nvertising for construction bids will\nfollow.\nNo immediate decision will be made\non the temporary postofflce \u2018location.\nThe problem of the lock boxes for\nmail is causing some didculty.\"\nFORMER SOUTH BEND\nGOLF PRO INJURED\nBy Intcrnational N>ws Service:\nMONROE. Micb., Dec. 18.\u2014Roy\nRobertson, former gold' professional\nat South Bend, suffered possible fa\n.tal injuries today in an automobile\nsmashup along the Tofedo-Monroe\nroad.\nRobertson, former golf professional\nnear his smashed automobile and was\nrushed to a hospital here. His skull\nwas fractured and his condition was\nserious. One leg was'broken in the\ncrash also. Robertson apparently was\ndriving alone when the accident oc\ncurred. No witnesses could be lo\ncated to explain how the accident\noccurred.\nIN SOUTH BENI)\nTODAY.\nExchange club, 12:15 o\u2019clock, Tur\nish room, Oliver.\nAssociates Investment Co., 645\no'clock. 'Florentine room, LaSalle\nColumbus Luncheon club, noon,\nKnights of Columbus hall.\nT\nDR. PAUL E. HALEY\nTO ASSIST COROTSER\nDr. Paul E. Haley, a \u2018graduate of\nthe University of Illinois, has been\nappointed deputy county coroner by\nCoroner-elect Dr. B. J. Bolka, it was\nannounced, Thursday.\nDr. Haley takes over the post which\nhas been held by Dr. W. K. Mikesch.\nHe was bom in Woodstock, 111.,\"in\n1901 and received his literary and\nmedical education at the University\nof Illinois.\nHe came to South Bend to serve an\ninterneship at the Epworth hospital,\nand for two years following that he\nwas surgical assistant to Dr. James L.\nWilson. He is now engaged in the\ngeneral practice of medicine and sur\ngery.\nDr. Haley is a member of the St.\nJoseph County Medical society, the\nIndiana State Medical association and\na Fellow of the American Medical as\nsociation.\nSALE OF SEALS\nGROWS STEADILY\nNear $9,000 Mark as\nCounty Schools Turn\nin Quota.\nChristmas seal sales are nearing\nthe $9,000 mark, leaving $6,000 worth\nto be sold to reach the county quota.\nSchool sales are in progress. Five\ndollars has been set as a goal. Miss\nOrpha Ryan\u2019s room and Miss Gladys\nEllingson\u2019s room in the Muessel school\nhave each reached the goal. These\nrooms will receive health bonds.\nMiss Martha Oster's room at\nSunnyside will win a $10 health bond.\nThe Notre Dame students and\nfaculty have to date purchased $78.28\nworth of Christmas seals.\n\u25a0Clay township contributions turned\nin yesterday amounted to $33.85; Cen\nter township had $7.70; German $4.45;\nGreene, $3; Harris, $5.50; Portage\n$4; Penn $19.90 and Warren $12.85.\nMary Pickford\u2019s and Bobby Jones\u2019\nsignatures on sheets of Christmas\nseals will be sold by auction tonight\nat 8:30 o\u2019clock.\nTWO ARE GRANTED\nDIVORCE DECREES\nDorothy Smith was granted a di\nvorce from her husband, Donald, and\nthe custody of their five-year-old son\nby Judge Orlo R. Dealil in Superior\ncourt No. 2, Wednesday afternoon\nMrs. Smith charged her nusband with\ncruelty.\nLuke Molnar was granted a di\nvorce in the same court on grounds\nof cruelty from his wife, Lena.\nRECEIVERSHIP CASE\nDELAYED IN COURT\nThe receivership against the Nicely\nBrothers Paper Co., of South Bend,\npetitioned for by the Albany Felt Co.,\non an unpaid obligation of $663, has\nbeen postponed until Jan. 7. The case\nwas filed in Superior court No. 2, and\nscheduled originally for a hearing\nWednesday afternoon.\nThe only time to catch Mrs. Lafe\nSnd at home is when the gang plays\nbridge at her house. It must be tough\nto be overwhelmin\u2019ly elected as a wet\nan\u2019 then have to siphon off a lot o\u2019\nhome brew an\u2019 cap'it.\nTAYLOR'S OFFICE\nDISMISSES BREW\nCASES IN COURT\nSchwartz Says He Will\nTry Cases Only on\nMerit.\nThe old bugbear of prosecuting at\ntorneys, the possession of homebrew\nbeer, may or may not receive some\nclose attention during the forthcom\ning regime of Sam P. Schwartz as\ncounty prosecutor.\nIn the face of what the adminis\ntration of Prosecutor Harry S. Tay\nlor has done in the prosecution of\nmen and women charged with the\npossession of homebrew beer,\nSchwartz, said Thursday that he had\nnot given the homebrew question any\nserious thought as a crime to be\ndealt with lightly if at all.\nThompson Dismisses Case\nDeputy Prosecutor Glenn' M.\nThompson dismissed a liquor law vio\nlation case against Myrtle Clark in\nthe Circuit court, Wednesday, be\ncause the evidence was insufficient.\nHe said she had only three bottles of\nhomebrew in her possession when ar\nrested.\nThe South Bend City court had\nlooked at the case in a different light.\nShe was found guilty and fined $125\nwith costs of $30. Her attorney\nGeorge A. Schock, appealed the case\nto the Circuit court, and when it was\ncalled for trial Wednesday, Thomp\nson filed a motion to dismiss the\ncase, thus nullifying^the action of the\nCity court.\nIt has been the complaint of prose\ncuting officials heretofore that home\nbrew beer cases could not \u00a3tand up in\ncourt, especially in front of a jury. It\nhas been the experience of such offi\ncials, so they say, that jurymen look\nupon homebrew lightly, and are in\nclined to find the defendants not\nguilty.\nNo Policy Decided On\nSchwartz, who takes office the first\nof the year, said he had formed no\npoltcy with regard to homebrew cases,\nand could not say at this time that\nhis office would not prosecute such\ncases.\nHe said that homebred cases which\nwould come up during his adminis\ntration would have to be handled on\ntheir respective merits, and that his\noffice could only approach such cases\nfrom the, point of view that such\nbeverages of illegal alcoholic con\ntent, were violating the law.\nTEACHERS TO GET\nJANUARYCHECKS\nUsual Six-Week1 Interim\nBetween Pay Days Is\nChanged.\nSouth Bend public school teachers\nreceived their last pay checks for this\nyear Thursday. Whether the rein\nforcements to the teachers\u2019 purses\nwill mean more Christmas presents\nfor someone could not be learned. At\nleast the teachers will not be without\nfunds over the holidays.\nMore than $100,000 is being dis\ntributed to approximately 600 teach\ners, R. D. Orcutt announced Thursday\nmorning.\nOrdinarily this \"pay, day\u201d is the\nlast the teachers have until the last\nof January. This means a stretch of\nsix weeks interim. This year, how\never, the board of education has\nmade arrangements to issue checks\ntwice during January. And the\nteachers will receive checks the mid\ndle of January.\nLIFE UNDERWRITERS\nTO HOLD LUNCHEON\nThe South Bend Life Underwrit\ners\u2019 association will hold its regular\nmonthly meeting Friday noon at the\nY. W. C. A. The session will be pre\nceded by a luncheon to which all\nmembers and those connected .with\nlife insurance companies are invited.\nArguyle Brown, manager of the\nMutual Life Insurance Co., as a di\nrector of the association will have\ncharge of the meeting. There will be\nno invited speaker but Mr. Brown\nwill make a report of the recent sales\ncongress held in Chicago.\nThe remainder of the program will\nbe developed by introducing members\nwho have recently become affiliated\nwith the organization and by short\ntalks of an informal nature.\nCOLLEGE observes\nFEAST OF CHRISTMAS\nSt. Mary's college celebrated the\nspiritual observance of the feast of\nChristmas, Wednesday night, with a\ncampus procession of the junior class\nsinging Christmas hymns and carols.\nThe procession circled the campus\nand led through the college build\nings exemplifying one of the oldest\ncampus traditions at the school. It\nwas the last of the pre-Christmas\nexercises, and on Thursday, classes\nwere dismissed and the girl students\nprepared to leave for their homes\nfor the Christmas holiday vacations.\nCRUELTY CHARGED\nIN DIVORCE BILL\nEtha Nunnally filed suit for a\ndivorce in the Circuit court Thurs\nday, charging her husband, Homer,\nwith cruelty. They were married\nJan. 10, 1820.\nWhat does a fireman do when he is not putting out fires? Right at this season of the year, in Mishawaka, he is helping Santa Claus, as the picture\nshows. A part of the Central fire station in Mishawaka is a workshop for the repair of toys to be given to needy children this ChjjJstmas time. This\ngroup of firemen seems to be enjoying this work which is so different from their regular duties.\nFIREMEN BRING CHRISTMAS JOY TO TOTS\nASSESSMENTCUT\nGIVEN BY DEAHL\nI\nI\nf\nFive Obtain Reduction of\n15 Per Cent in Street\nCosts.\nThe modified assessment roll of the j\ncity of Mishawaka for certain street\nimprovements made there, which was\nattacked in an appeal to Superior\ncourt No. 2, by several property own\ners, was modified still further Thurs\nday as a result of a judgment\nhanded down by Judge Orlo R.\nDeahl.\nAssessments for street improve\nments, which Leon and August Bock,\nthe North Side Land and Improve\nment Co., Gertrude O\u2019Neill and Jo\nseph Scheininger have assailed in\ncourt as too excessive and far beyond j\nthe amount of benefit received by the\nproperty, were reduced about 15 per\ncent for the assessment which had\npreviously been modified by the Mish\nawaka board of works.\nCity Attorney I. K. Parks said\nThursday, that the reduction of 15\nper cent in the assessment was\nvirtually a compromise between the\ncity and the plaintiffs, the latter\nhave sought a reduction of about 30\nper cent.\nTIRES PUNCTURES\nON SEVEN AUTOS\nVandal Slashes Casings\nas Owners Attend Re\nvival Here.\nWhen attendants at a revival ser\nvice in Christ Temple. Elwood avenue\nand Elmer street, left the services\nWednesday night, seven members of\nthe congregation found that the tires\nof their automobiles had been punc\ntured by some vandal.\nThe police were notified, and a\nsearch for the vandal was being con\ntinued Thursday, although no ar\nrests had been made at a late hour.\n.Not satisfied with puncturing just\none tire, the vandal cut four tires on\neach of the seven cars, and wherever\nthere was a spare time, it, too, was\npunctured.\nThe work of the vandal was re\nported to police headquarters by the\nRev. Charles Taylor.\nThose whose tires were punctured\nare Gorden Hensell, New Carlisle;\nA. R -Morgan, 805 Meridian street,\nMishawaka; P. E. Carlson, 208 E.\nBronson street; Oscar Wise, rural\nroute No. 4; J. R. Freeman, Dowagiac,\nMich.; Chester Menill, 226 N. Sadie\nstreet, and Clyde Cagjer, 532 Vi S. Co\nlumbia street\nLAPORTEAN GRANTED\nINVENTION PATENT\ni Special to The Xews-TImei:\nWASHINGTON, Dec. 18.\u2014John A.\nSecor, LaPorte. was granted a patent\ntoday for a method of and apparatus\nfer reatomizing fuel. He filed h;s ap\nplication Feb. 17, 1928. Twelve claims\nfor new ideas were allowed. The\npatent has been assigned to the Ad\nvance-Rumely Co.\nV 1\n'Police Raid on Rotary Party\nAids Night Club Atmosphere\nHOST OF SKATERS\nGATHERS AT RINKS\nDESPITE POOR ICE\nHundreds of skaters enjoyed the\nsport at rinks in seven city parks\nWednesday afternoon and evening.\nThe best skating was to be found\nat the Potawatomi park pool.\nRising temperature Thursday\nwas expected to interfere with the\nskating. Park authorities have\nfound difficulty in building up a\nsmooth skating surface at the va\nrious rinks.\nRECEIVER NAMED\nIN CAB BUSINESS\nPeyton to Handle Affairs\nof Colonial Taxi on\nPetition.\nE. J. Peyton was named receiver\nfor the Colonial Cab Co., by Judge\nOrlo R. Deahl in Superior court No.\n2, Wednesday afternoon, on the pe\ntition of Ross L. Jordan, who com\nplained that the company was unable\nto pay him certain^ obligations it had\ncontracted.\nThe petition was filed some time ago\nfollowing considerable agitation here\nover the methods employed by va\nrious taxi cab companies in conduct\ning their business.\nThe Colonial Cab Co., was one of\nthe concerns which did not own all\nof its own cabs, instead it charged\ndrivers who owned automobiles, a\ncertain fee for operating under the\ncompany\u2019s name and for the con\nvenience of the company\u2019s telephone\nheadquarters.\nReceiver Peyton was instructed by\nthe court to operate the business un\ntil such time as he could liquidate it\nsubject to the approval of the court.\nVETERANS TO HOLD\nCHARITY PROGRAM\nA charity party will be held by\nmembers of the Veterans of Foreign\nWars, South Bend Post 1167, in the\nVeterans\u2019 hall, 303 Vi S. Michigan\nstreet, Friday night. Proceeds from\nthe affair will be used for the benefit\nof the needy ex-service men and\nfamilies- in this city. Baskets will be\ndelivered on Christmas morning and\nrelief work will continue throughout\nthe winter.\nSERVICES HELD FOR\nWOMAN AT CULVER\nSpfrlal to The Newt-Times;\nCULVER, IND., Dec. 18.\u2014Funeral\nservices for Mrs. Mary A. Castleman,\n68, wife of William Castleman, five\nmiles northwest of Culver, were, held\nat 1:30 o\u2019clock Thursday afternoon at\nthe Culver Evangelical church. The\nRev. J. S. Appleman, Plymouth, offici\nated. Burial was in the Qilver ceme\ntery.\nMrs. Castleman died at 10 o\u2019clock\ni Tuesday morning at her nome here. _\nOfficers discover Fluid\nin Small Bottles Is\nHarmless.\n\u201cWhat\u2019s going on here?\u2019\u2019 inquired\nCaptain \u201cBig Bill\u201d Hosinski, as he\nand six aides from the South Bend\npolice department interrupted the\nRotary club\u2019s Night Club Christmas\nparty Wednesday night in the Oliver\nhotel soon after it had got underway.\n\u201cWhy, what do you mean? Weren\u2019t\nwe to be protected?\u201d was the ques\ntioning response from Miss Lydia\nLindfoerg, manager of the Oliver hotel\ntea shop, who as hostess of the party\nwas in the act of welcoming her\nguests.\n\u201cYou never paid me a cent for pro\ntection,\u201d insisted \u201cBig Bill.\u201d\nAbout this time many respectable\nSouth Bend citizens who were pa\ntronizing the party because it had'\nbeen advertised as a means of raising\nfunds for charity, began to think they\nhad taken this idea of benevolence\ntoo far. Besides they felt assured\nthat the quarter pint bottles at each\nplat contained harmless cider, despite\nits Scotch y color.\nHas Serious Look\nThe affair began to take on serious\naspects, until Will G. Grabill stepped\nforward asking \u201cBill\u201d to sample the\ncontents. He did and so did the six\naides.\nYes, it was cider, and though cha\ngrined, the copers laughed it off,\nand went their ways, leaving the\nparty unmolested.\nThis hoax and a dozen others, ar\nranged by Bari J. Redden, program\nchairman, made the Rotary club\u2019s so\ncial gathering one of the most elab\norate in its history. It was attended\nby 375 guests, and all proceeds taken\nfrom ticket sales, auctioning of prizes\nand other ways will go to the club\u2019s\ncharity fund.\nAfter dinner, Rabbi William M.\nStem took charge of auctioning\nprizes, while the Rotary room was\ncleared for -the entertainment pro\ngram.\nGive Impersonations\nOf the vaudeville acts the most\npopular was a John McCormack\nbroadcast performed by Kenneth G.\nMerrill and Rabbi Stem. Rome C.\nStephenson and Robert Swintz con\nducted an Amos, \u2019n Andy act, and\n.Thomas A. Hynes impersonated K. K.\nRockne.\nW. K. Lamport was introduaed as\nWill Rogers, but turned out to be\nnone other than Ed Wynne.\nMusical selections were given by\nBelden Ieonard, violinist; Ray Win\nthers, guitarist; Mrs. Anne Christ\nman Waechter, contralto; Miss Helen\nChristman, soprano; and by the\nMyron Walz orchestra.\nDancing followed the program. Red\nand green streamers, balloons, noise\nmakers and paper caps also con\ntributed a night, club atmosphere to\nthe affair.\nMAGICIANS OF CITY\nORGANIZE SOCIETY\nA South Bend ring of the Inter\nnational Brotherhood of Magicians\nhas been organized with the follow\ning .amateur magicians as members:\nH. B. Kresge. Julius Altfeld, Robert\nD. Orcutt. Otto Curl. Alex Nagy,\nPhilip Foxwell. Stephen Gubi and\nBenjamin Dribin. The ring will meet\nJan. 6 to elect officers.\nDR. MYERS.NAMED\nIN SANITY PROBE\nPhysicians to Examine\nPrisoner Facing Mur\nder Trial.\nDr. Edgar G. Myers was appointed\nby Special Judge Lewis W. Hammond\nThursday to serve on the sanity\ncommission in the Myers-Apple mur\nder case in place of Dr. Alfred S. Gi\no: dano, who was appointed last week,\nbut informed the court that he would\nbe unable to serve.\nDr. James A. McMeel is the other\nmember of the commission who will\nparticipate in the examination of\nGeorge Sherman Myers to determine\nhis mental soundness.\nMyers is charged in an indictment\nwith the rape and murder of nine\nyear-old Marverine Apple last August,\nand if convicted of first degree mur\nder committed under the circum\nstances of rape, faces death in the\nelectric chair with no other punish\nj ment as an alternative.\nTaylor in Oklahoma.\nHis trial is tentatively scheduled\nfor next Monday,, as is also the \"trial\nof Alexander B. Shipman for false\npretense iii the sile of stock in an\noil development project in Oklahoma.\nWhich case will be tried depends\nupon whether the Shipman case will\nbe ready. State's Attorney Harry S.\nTaylor is reported to be in Tulsa,\nOk la., now securing depositions to be\nused against Shipman.\nThe sanity commission to examine\nMyers was appointed after attorneys\nfor the accused man submitted a plea\nof insanity as well as a plea of not\nguilty. Drs. Myers and McMeel will\ntestify as court witnesses at the con\nclusion of the case.\nMRS. CHARLES BARR\nDIES AT DANVILLE\nMrs. Charles Barr, 52. Danville, HI.,\nwho formerly lived at 608 W. Jeffer\nson street, died at 4:50 o\u2019clock Tues\nday afternoon at the Sit. Elizabeth\nhospital, Danville, following an illness\nof two months.\nMrs. Barr moved from South Bend\nto Danville three years ago with her\nhusband, after ilving in this city for\nsix years. She is survived by her\nhusband, after living in this city for\nDetroit, Mich.\nShe was bom in Portsmouth, O.,\nJan. 7, 1878, and was married 29 years\nago in that city.\nFuneral services will be held Fri\nday in Portsmouth. Mr. Jnd Mrs.\nClifford Bickel, 719 N. Main street,\nleft Thursday morning to attend the\nfuneral.\nLOCAL POLICEMAN IS\nCITED FOR CONTEMPT\nLaFayette Riddle, Negro South\nBend policeman, appeared in Su\nperior court in Fort Wayne Wednes\nday charged with failure to make\nalimony payments. His former wife,\nJosie Riddle, was granted a divorce\nfrom him in 1925 and custody of their\nthree children. Riddle was cited for\ncontempt of court and hailed before\nthe Fort Wayne judge when he is\nalleged to have failed to keep up\nweekly payments.\nPoliceman Riddle agreed to pay up\ni and on this understanding the case\nI was continued until Dec. 22.\nMAN DISAPPEARS\nFROM HOME; FIND\nCAR NEAR RIVER\nLos$ of Position Believed\nto Have Prompted\nSuicide?.\nPolice Thursday were dragging the\nSt. Joseph river near the Pour-Mile\nbridge for the body of E. H. Cornish,\n60, rural route 6, Niles, Mich., who is\nbelieved to have thrown himself into\nthe stream over the loss of his posi\ntion as manager of the, State Line\nLumber Co.\nMr. Cornish\u2019s automobile was found\nearly Wednesday night at the bridge\nafter he had been missing from the\nlumber company\u2019s offices on the Indi\nana and Michigan state line since 9\no\u2019clock Wednesday morning.\nWhen Mr. Cornish, who had been\ngiven a two-weeks notice last Friday\nthat another man was to take his\nplace as manager, left the lumber\ncompany offices Wednesday morning,\nhe said that he would return in' a;\nshort while. i\nFails to Return\nLate Wednesday afternoon Mrs.\nCornish visited the offices, saying that\nher husband had not been to dinner\nand that she was worried about him.'\nImmedately relatives and friends of\nthe missing man were telephoned, but\nno trace of Mr. Cornish could be\nfound.\nLater Henry Kubiak, a neighbor of\nMr. and Mrs. Cornish, who reside a\nshort distance from the lumber com\npany\u2019s offices, on the Michigan side\nof th% state line, saw Mr. Cornish\u2019s\nautomobile near the Four-Mile bridge,\nand as soon as possible he notified\nMrs. Cornish and the company offici\nals.\nIt was learned Thursday that Mr.\nCornish\u2019s car had been standing at\nthe bridge since early Wednesday\nmorning, which leads police to believe\nthat he plunged into the river early\nin the day.\nIt was not until Mr. Kubiak saw\nthe car that its presence at the bridge\nwas made known to Mrs. Cornish and\nthe lumber company officials were\nnotified.\nNotify Sheriff\nSheriff Thomas A. Goodrick was\nnotified and a search for Mr. Corn-'\nish was begun, although it was be\nlieved that he had thrown himself in\nto the river. As soon as possible\nThursday, the work of dragging the\nstream for the body was begun.\nNo farewell note was found in the\ncar, although Mr. Cornish\u2019s insurance\npolicy on the automobile was found\non the seat of the machine.\nAccording to E. R. Newland, South\nBend, president of the State Line\nLumber Co., Mr. Cornish, who had\nbeen manager of the company for the\nlast five years, was told that a young-\ner executive would take his place on\nthe following Monday, and gave Mr.\nCornish tworweeks nptice.\nRelatives Aid Police\nMr. Newland said he explained the\ncircumstances to Mr. Cornish as gent\nly as possible, and in doing so told\nthe retiring manager that if at the\nend of two weeks he had not obtained\nanother position, arrangements where\nby he would be kept on the payroll in\nanother capacity would be made.\nI According to Mr. Newland, Mr.\nCornish had an appointment with\nsomeone Tuesday regarding another\nposition, but Mr. Newland did not\nknow the one with whom Mr. Corn\nish conferred.\nMr. Cornish\u2019s absence from, the of\nfices Wednesday did not excite any\nconcern as he had been told that he\nwould be allowed any necessary time\noff from his duties in searching for,\nanother position.\nPolice were being aided in the work\nof dragging the river Thursday by!\nEdward Stanfield, 513 31st street, a\nson-in-law of Mr. Cornish, and J. F.\nFink, 519 36th street, a stepson of\nthe missing man.\nNAME DIVIDENDS\nFOR CHAIN GROUP\nInterstate Department\nStore Announce\nQuarterly.\nThe regular quarterly dividend ot\n50 cents a share on common stock\nwas declared Thursday by directors\nof Interstate Department Stores, Ind.,\nof which the Grand Leader store In\nSouth Bend is a member.\nAccording to word received by Jos\neph Scheininger, proprietor of the\nlocal store, this dividend, making the\ncommon dividend $2 a share annu\nally, was recommended by Leo G.\nFederman, president of the Inter\nstate.\n\u201cThe sales record of the company\nfor the year shows to excellent ad\nvantage in comparison with the Fed\neral Reserve data,\u201d Mr. Federman\nsaid.\nHILDEBRAND-NELSON\nDEAL IS AUTHORIZED\nElmer Rodgers, receiver Tot the\nHildebrand-Nelson Co., was author-,\nized by Judge Orlo R. Deahl, Wed\nnesday afternoon, to sell the build\nings and personal property of the\ncompany to D. D. Perry for $6,000.\nRodgers set out in his petition that\nthe concern was insolvent and that\nunless a sale was made, there was\nlittle likelihood of realizing anything\nfrom the assets of the company by\nI trying to operate it.\nThe receivership was instituted by\nI the Edwards Iron Co., of South Bend.","height":"32508","width":"24312"}}
